We follow the hints and first rewrite the integral.

\begin{align*}\int_1^2 \frac{e^{1/x}}{x^2}\,dx = \int_1^2 x^{-2}e^{x^{-1}}\,dx.\end{align*}
Now we substitute

\begin{align*}u = x^{-1}, \quad \frac{du}{dx} = -x^{-2}, \quad dx = -x^2\,du.\end{align*}
Further, for $x=1$ we have $u=1$, and for $x=2$ we have $u=1/2$.
Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\int_1^2 x^{-2}e^{x^{-1}}\,dx &= \int_1^{1/2} x^{-2}e^u(-x^2\,du) \\
&= -\int_1^{1/2} e^u\,du \\
&= \int_{1/2}^1 e^u\,du \\
&= \left.e^{u}\right|_{1/2}^1 \\
&= e-e^{1/2}.\end{align*}
